  "opinion": "As a woman in my late forties who's been working in fitness for over two decades, I've seen firsthand how science often feels like a world built for others. The gender gap in science isn't just about fewer women in labs or universities—it's about the invisible barriers that make it feel impossible for many of us to even try. Growing up in a small Italian town, I learned early that science was seen as a 'man's field,' and even though my parents both had college degrees, they never spoke much about their own careers in STEM. I remember sitting with my dad after school, watching him fix things with his hands, and wondering why science seemed so far from what we did at home. Now, as a fitness trainer in Milan, I see this gap every day. My clients often ask me how I got into science—sometimes they think it's a job for men. The truth is, science isn't a single field; it's a collection of disciplines, and the gap affects everyone differently. But here's what I believe: we absolutely should address it. It's not just about fairness—it's about building a future where everyone has the chance to contribute. For me, it starts with simple things like listening to women's voices in science, creating safe spaces for conversations, and making sure that science is taught in schools in a way that's accessible to all. I've noticed that when I talk to my clients about their goals, they often feel like they're the only ones who can't do it. So, I try to share my own journey, showing that science isn't something you have to be 'good at' to do—it's about curiosity and care. In a world where so many people feel disconnected from science, I think the best way to close the gap is to start with the people who already have it—like me—and make sure they feel seen, heard, and valued. Because if we don't, we're not just missing out on talent; we're missing out on the full potential of humanity.",
